    <item>
      <title>Mocking Authentication and Authorization in ASP.NET Core Integration Tests</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/auth-in-integration-tests/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 12 Dec 2021 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/auth-in-integration-tests/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;ASP.NET Core makes writing integration tests very easy and even fun. One aspect that might be a bit tough to figure out is authentication and authorization. We might want to run integration tests under different users and different roles.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;To get started, let&amp;rsquo;s assume we have an endpoint like this:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#f0f0f0;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-cs&#34; data-lang=&#34;cs&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f&#34;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;app.MapGet(&lt;span style=&#34;color:#4070a0&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;hi&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;, (HttpContext httpContext) =&amp;gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f&#34;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;{&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f&#34;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;    &lt;span style=&#34;color:#902000&#34;&gt;var&lt;/span&gt; userId = httpContext.User?.Claims?.FirstOrDefault(c =&amp;gt; c.Type == ClaimTypes.NameIdentifier)?.Value;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f&#34;&gt;4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f&#34;&gt;5&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;    &lt;span style=&#34;color:#007020;font-weight:bold&#34;&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#4070a0&#34;&gt;$&amp;#34;Hello #{userId}&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f&#34;&gt;6&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;}).RequireAuthorization();&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s a very simple endpoint. It gets the currently logged in user&amp;rsquo;s ID and says hello to them.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
